prehend death as a collective, multispecies event. Sister Death proposes an alternative view in which life and death are not mortal enemies destined for mutual destruction. Instead, they are engaged in a contested, tense, and sometimes mutually empowering form of connection—a sisterhood.Eloquent and approachable, this book deftly integrates the insights of a number of disciplines to provide a profound reconsideration of the relations between life and death. Sister Death also features a series of original works by the artist Krista Dragomer that stage an ongoing conceptual conversation with the text.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeathxPolitical aspects. 0aDeathxReligious aspects. 0aPolitical theology. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh  aChristian political theology.  aJacques Derrida.  aKrista Dragomer.  aSaint Francis of Assisi.  aSister Death.  aToni Morrison.  acontinental philosophy.  acritical life studies.  acritical race theory.  adeath and dying.  adeath positivity.  aenvironmental humanities.  alife and death.  amortality studies.  amortality.  apsychoanalysis.  areligious philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023 Englishz978311131928508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2023z9783111318820oZDB-23-DGF0 cprintz978023120836940uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/maro2083640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978023